on the streets.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:38.209
Prof: Okay that's good.
 

00:01:38.209 --> 00:01:43.494
In the--he also mentions three
American novelists in the back,

00:01:43.494 --> 00:01:45.400
did you notice that?
 

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:46.239
Student:  No, I did not.
 

00:01:46.239 --> 00:01:48.180
Prof: Okay.
 

00:01:48.180 --> 00:01:52.510
Well it's interesting,
the--I'll quote him--

00:01:52.510 --> 00:01:55.644
the influences on White
Tiger are three black

00:01:55.644 --> 00:01:58.411
American writers of the post
World War II era:

00:01:58.411 --> 00:02:00.365
Ralph Ellison,
James Baldwin,

00:02:00.365 --> 00:02:01.489
and Richard Wright.
 

00:02:01.489 --> 00:02:08.632
It has many ways to look at it,
it is written in a very

00:02:08.632 --> 00:02:15.774
straightforward style that
is--each paragraph is pretty

00:02:15.774 --> 00:02:18.419
straightforward.
 

00:02:18.419 --> 00:02:24.959
The subtext about how it's
being told is a little more

00:02:24.959 --> 00:02:29.754
complicated,
and one of the other things he

00:02:29.754 --> 00:02:33.211
says in the back which--
and this goes to the point

00:02:33.211 --> 00:02:36.586
Sophie made,
is that while none of the

00:02:36.586 --> 00:02:42.830
characters or incidents are
copied out of journalism,

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:47.623
which is the author's business,
all of them are meant to be

00:02:47.623 --> 00:02:51.840
representative of something real
in Indian life,

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:56.419
so that the book is literally
fiction,

00:02:56.419 --> 00:03:01.250
but has a purpose like many of
the best works of fiction,

00:03:01.250 --> 00:03:07.280
has a purpose of describing
something that is very real.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:10.738
Are there ways in which fiction
can do a better job than social

00:03:10.738 --> 00:03:13.360
science of telling the truth
about a country?

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:20.250
Anybody got a thought about
that?

00:03:20.250 --> 00:03:21.788
Yes?
 

00:03:21.788 --> 00:03:24.710
Student:  Well it's an
art form,

00:03:24.710 --> 00:03:26.543
and something like social
science can't really say well

00:03:26.543 --> 00:03:29.417
this makes me feel this,
or this is like the nuance of

00:03:29.417 --> 00:03:31.750
that,
and that's where art plays in.

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:33.815
I mean--also,
I mean, it's mass media too in

00:03:33.815 --> 00:03:35.785
a lot of ways,
so you can reach a lot more

00:03:35.785 --> 00:03:38.378
people through this and have it
easily understood.

00:03:38.378 --> 00:03:40.690
Prof: Okay,
its mass media,

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:45.030
but it actually does something
that most non-fiction written by

00:03:45.030 --> 00:03:48.245
academics can't do;
economists, political

00:03:48.245 --> 00:03:52.604
scientists, people like that,
by and large a little wooden

00:03:52.604 --> 00:03:56.810
and rigid, little category
bound, a little obsessed with

00:03:56.810 --> 00:03:58.110
methodology.
 

00:03:58.110 --> 00:04:05.420
And this book covers a huge
swath of very complicated

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:11.161
aspects of a society which,
as far as I can tell,

00:04:11.161 --> 00:04:15.288
is top half dozen in the way of
complexity in the world.

00:04:15.288 --> 00:04:21.620
I mean the structure of--the
historical structure of India

00:04:21.620 --> 00:04:28.062
and the incredible rate of
economic and sociological change

00:04:28.062 --> 00:04:31.949
have very few equals elsewhere.
 

