like, now modern India.
 

00:30:23.069 --> 00:30:25.288
Prof: Good.
 

00:30:25.288 --> 00:30:30.930
The other layer is captured in
the line in the book,

00:30:30.930 --> 00:30:34.526
"there is no hatred like
that of the number two servant

00:30:34.526 --> 00:30:36.660
for the number one
servant."

00:30:36.660 --> 00:30:42.315
That close conflict we
recognize--you see that

00:30:42.315 --> 00:30:49.480
everywhere around here,
you see it even on the faculty.

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:51.529
Susie Park?
 

00:30:51.529 --> 00:30:54.858
That's the question.
 

00:30:54.858 --> 00:31:05.182
I was going to ask you about
servant hostility to servant and

00:31:05.182 --> 00:31:06.558
so on.
 

00:31:06.558 --> 00:31:11.123
Student:  Well I
guess--well basically it's kind

00:31:11.123 --> 00:31:15.009
of similar to servant hostility
to masters,

00:31:15.009 --> 00:31:17.160
I think, because,
like, when you look at,

00:31:17.160 --> 00:31:20.220
like, the person to person,
like you're not actually hating

00:31:20.220 --> 00:31:24.238
the person themselves,
but more like--because

00:31:24.238 --> 00:31:28.434
you're--like he has this,
kind of like,

00:31:28.434 --> 00:31:30.750
bitterness at the system
itself,

00:31:30.750 --> 00:31:33.367
but then, like,
in some parts of the book it

