00:32:08.563 --> 00:32:10.088
the household.
 

00:32:10.088 --> 00:32:19.603
Nafez the--there's--I think one
of the great lines in the book

00:32:19.603 --> 00:32:26.400
is the one about the coop;
the chicken coop is guarded

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:27.569
from within.
 

00:32:27.569 --> 00:32:29.058
What's all that?
 

00:32:29.058 --> 00:32:31.329
Student:  I mean the way
I interpret it was it's more

00:32:31.329 --> 00:32:33.308
like a social construct,
where I mean if you just look

00:32:33.308 --> 00:32:35.923
at the back of the book it says,
Balram Halawi is a complicated

00:32:35.923 --> 00:32:37.236
man servant,
philosopher,

00:32:37.236 --> 00:32:39.306
entrepreneur,
etc., but when you're inside

00:32:39.306 --> 00:32:42.640
the coop you're only thinking of
how can I be a better servant.

00:32:42.640 --> 00:32:44.038
So it's a social construct
whereby,

00:32:44.038 --> 00:32:46.078
I mean, we can even relate it
to the hatred of servant one--

00:32:46.078 --> 00:32:48.930
servant two to servant one is
because the servant--

00:32:48.930 --> 00:32:50.250
you're not thinking of becoming
a master,

00:32:50.250 --> 00:32:53.048
what you're aspiring to is
servant one,

00:32:53.048 --> 00:32:56.134
and it just scares you to get
out of that social construct and

00:32:56.134 --> 00:32:59.321
the only way to get out of it is
to resolve to something extreme

00:32:59.321 --> 00:33:00.788
like killing your master.
 

00:33:00.788 --> 00:33:05.832
Prof: Okay so that often
the victims of a hugely

00:33:05.832 --> 00:33:11.435
oppressive situation are hostile
more to people who are their

00:33:11.435 --> 00:33:16.291
peers or near peers then to
people who are their vast

00:33:16.291 --> 00:33:20.451
superiors,
and that's a pretty good

00:33:20.451 --> 00:33:23.130
generalization actually.
 

00:33:23.130 --> 00:33:26.230
Sebastian?
 

00:33:26.230 --> 00:33:32.930
There we are.
 

00:33:32.930 --> 00:33:36.509
Tell us about the car accident.
 

00:33:36.509 --> 00:33:40.660
Student:  All right,
so in page 137 there's a--

00:33:40.660 --> 00:33:45.098
Pinky Madam decides that she
wants to drive,

00:33:45.098 --> 00:33:47.769
tells the driver to get out,
then she comes back,

00:33:47.769 --> 00:33:50.250
she's very drunk at this point,
comes back,

00:33:50.250 --> 00:33:53.857
gets in--tells the driver to
get back in the car and then

00:33:53.857 --> 00:33:55.920
drives off and hits something.
 

00:33:55.920 --> 00:34:00.701
At first we don't know what it
is, we quickly discover it's a

00:34:00.701 --> 00:34:05.145
child,
and everyone's kind of in shock

00:34:05.145 --> 00:34:07.759
and I think--
I don't know if you want me to

00:34:07.759 --> 00:34:09.059
say more of the details of the
accident,

00:34:09.059 --> 00:34:13.550
but the biggest implication is
that then Balram is asked to

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.340
take the blame for this
accident,

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:22.190
this master's wife committed.
 

00:34:22.190 --> 00:34:26.619
Instead of thinking of how he
cannot take the blame,

00:34:26.619 --> 00:34:29.161
he kind of starts automatically
assuming how am I going to

00:34:29.161 --> 00:34:31.550
survive in jail,
what am I going to do to

00:34:31.550 --> 00:34:32.130
survive?
 

00:34:32.130 --> 00:34:35.704
I think it goes back to that
thing that we were just talking

00:34:35.704 --> 00:34:38.735
about on the rooster coop,
where it's just absolute

00:34:38.735 --> 00:34:42.115
perpetual servitude;
it's kind of very much

00:34:42.115 --> 00:34:43.079
intrinsic.
 

00:34:43.079 --> 00:34:44.800
Prof: Okay, good.
 

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:47.724
Now--and what this is
straightforward-

00:34:47.724 --> 00:34:50.809
-straightforward criminal
corruption.

00:34:50.809 --> 00:35:02.304
It's a criminal act that the
Kosh couple are committing and

00:35:02.304 --> 00:35:11.619
The White Tiger basically just
lives with it.

00:35:11.619 --> 00:35:18.090
Later in the book--Ann where
are you?

00:35:18.090 --> 00:35:25.367
Later in the book the concept
of rage gets to be center stage,

00:35:25.367 --> 00:35:29.842
I think on page 196 is it;
help us with that,

00:35:29.842 --> 00:35:31.539
what's going on with that?
 

00:35:31.539 --> 00:35:35.240
Student:  Well I think
to a certain extent he realizes

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:38.818
that the only way for him to
escape kind of from the rooter

00:35:38.818 --> 00:35:41.039
coop is to do something extreme.
 

00:35:41.039 --> 00:35:44.362
One thing that he talks about
when he describes the whole

00:35:44.362 --> 00:35:47.864
rooster coop analogy is that
like he mentions family as part

00:35:47.864 --> 00:35:49.289
of that explanation.
 

00:35:49.289 --> 00:35:52.849
He says that family is like the
thing--

00:35:52.849 --> 00:35:56.650
that family is the thing that
keeps you in the coop and so I

00:35:56.650 --> 00:36:00.389
think like he needs a really
powerful emotion to counteract

00:36:00.389 --> 00:36:03.159
the family ties in order to
break free.

00:36:03.159 --> 00:36:08.266
Prof: Okay,
so he's in two different

00:36:08.266 --> 00:36:13.981
coercive networks,
one to do with his own family

00:36:13.981 --> 00:36:20.789
and another to do with the
family which employs him.

00:36:20.789 --> 00:36:23.590
Jake are you here?
 

00:36:23.590 --> 00:36:29.603
The most dramatic passage in
the book has to do with the

00:36:29.603 --> 00:36:33.539
ulterior uses of a whiskey
bottle.

00:36:33.539 --> 00:36:35.730
Student:  Right.
 

00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:43.210
Balram uses the bottle to kill
the son of his employer,

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:46.956
and he does this to steal the
money that Ashok was going to

00:36:46.956 --> 00:36:49.670
use to bribe officials and he's
go off,

00:36:49.670 --> 00:36:51.829
takes it, and starts his own
life.

00:36:51.829 --> 00:36:54.806
Prof: Okay,
how do you interpret what he

00:36:54.806 --> 00:36:55.260
does?
 

00:36:55.260 --> 00:37:01.159
Student:  I saw it sort
of emblematic of the new India,

00:37:01.159 --> 00:37:08.570
sort of taking over and sort of
replacing the old India,

00:37:08.570 --> 00:37:12.030
that Ashok and his family are
sort of representative of

00:37:12.030 --> 00:37:14.530
because he's the son of a
landowner,

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:17.262
he's wealthy,
and he's using his money to try

00:37:17.262 --> 00:37:20.679
to keep himself in power by
bribing these officials,

00:37:20.679 --> 00:37:24.128
and Ashok takes that money--or
Balram takes the money and he

00:37:24.128 --> 00:37:27.460
goes and uses it to sort of
start his own business and get

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:28.980
himself up to the top.
 

00:37:28.980 --> 00:37:31.510
Prof: As he says an act
of entrepreneurship.

00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:33.789
Student:  Right.
 

00:37:33.789 --> 00:37:42.880
Prof: There was a huge
amount of parody in this.

00:37:42.880 --> 00:37:45.659
Do you think--how do you judge
him for this?

00:37:45.659 --> 00:37:50.661
Student:  I mean I would
say that it was--I wouldn't

00:37:50.661 --> 00:37:54.630
condone it, but I can sort of
understand it.

00:37:54.630 --> 00:37:58.911
Prof: Would you go so
far as to say justifiable

00:37:58.911 --> 00:37:59.800
homicide?
 

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:04.530
Student:  Not
justifiable in the sense that

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:06.523
he--
the man that he murdered

00:38:06.523 --> 00:38:09.327
deserved it,
but for him it was the only way

00:38:09.327 --> 00:38:12.840
to break out of the life that he
had been living and--

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:16.992
to me it just sort of--it
really captured just how

00:38:16.992 --> 00:38:21.652
traumatic for a society--
a change like modernization can

00:38:21.652 --> 00:38:21.960
be.
 

00:38:21.960 --> 00:38:25.889
Everyone's scrambling to get
themselves ahead and in the

00:38:25.889 --> 00:38:28.889
process people get stepped on,
people--

00:38:28.889 --> 00:38:31.889
Prof: Okay so you see it
as a rational act?

00:38:31.889 --> 00:38:32.159
Student:  Yeah.
 

00:38:32.159 --> 00:38:33.840
Prof: Not an act of rage?
 

00:38:33.840 --> 00:38:37.231
Student:  Yeah I think
it was definitely a rational

00:38:37.231 --> 00:38:39.909
act, but I don't know if that
justifies it.

00:38:39.909 --> 00:38:43.300
Prof: Okay well I don't
think it justifies it.

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:49.389
I'm not much on justifiable
homicide as a cultural trope,

00:38:49.389 --> 00:38:54.719
but it makes it easy to
understand, doesn't it?

00:38:54.719 --> 00:38:59.210
Amy Chu in the law school has a
book about--

00:38:59.210 --> 00:39:02.980
it begins with a story from her
own family in the Philippines,

00:39:02.980 --> 00:39:10.018
and in it her grandmother is
murdered by the family chauffer.

00:39:10.018 --> 00:39:21.666
The police record where motive
is recorded as just one word:

00:39:21.666 --> 00:39:23.639
revenge.
 

00:39:23.639 --> 00:39:30.054
And the relationship between
people who are completely

00:39:30.054 --> 00:39:34.289
dependent servants of
arbitrary--

00:39:34.289 --> 00:39:39.500
families who behave arbitrarily
and cruelly,

00:39:39.500 --> 00:39:43.204
this is an ancient story,
and it's one that's easy to

00:39:43.204 --> 00:39:44.130
understand.
 

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:50.110
Now let's get back to bigger
picture.

00:39:50.110 --> 00:39:53.199
Why is Balram so weak?
 

00:39:53.199 --> 00:39:57.300
Well there's--I had another--I
asked somebody about English

00:39:57.300 --> 00:39:59.139
language, who did I ask?
 

00:39:59.139 --> 00:40:01.429
Okay then I'll ask myself.
 

00:40:01.429 --> 00:40:06.483
English plays a huge part in
the class structure of a society

00:40:06.483 --> 00:40:07.579
like India.
 

00:40:07.579 --> 00:40:16.130
The--let's just list Balram's
weaknesses economically.

00:40:16.130 --> 00:40:23.248
One is English is not his first
language, his family and the

00:40:23.248 --> 00:40:26.869
debt to The Stork,
was it--

00:40:26.869 --> 00:40:29.514
Student:  And the debt
was the brother and sister

00:40:29.514 --> 00:40:29.900
dowry.
 

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:30.670
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:40:30.670 --> 00:40:35.253
The debt which gets him jerked
out of school and which is a

00:40:35.253 --> 00:40:39.760
constant burden to the family,
that's another weakness.

00:40:39.760 --> 00:40:43.858
He drops out of school because
his uncle rips him out of school

00:40:43.858 --> 00:40:45.380
actually, forcefully.
 

00:40:45.380 --> 00:40:47.210
Other weaknesses?
 

00:40:47.210 --> 00:40:51.130
Caste, he is not from an
advantaged caste.

00:40:51.130 --> 00:40:55.938
Sweet makers,
I don't quite understand why

00:40:55.938 --> 00:41:02.269
that disadvantage but--what
about the world demographic

00:41:02.269 --> 00:41:04.030
transition?
 

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:07.574
The world demographic
transition bearing down on this

00:41:07.574 --> 00:41:08.869
young man at all?
 

00:41:08.869 --> 00:41:15.556
Yes because the huge surge of
population in the darkness of

00:41:15.556 --> 00:41:22.242
India creates a devastatingly
plentiful supply of unskilled

00:41:22.242 --> 00:41:28.467
labor so that the market
equilibrium price of unskilled

00:41:28.467 --> 00:41:32.949
labor is very,
very low.

00:41:32.949 --> 00:41:38.525
The standards you have to use
in treating employees in

00:41:38.525 --> 00:41:44.835
unskilled or semi-skilled jobs
in order to keep them with you

00:41:44.835 --> 00:41:46.730
are near zero.
 

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:50.672
Rickshaw puller,
rickshaw pullers have

00:41:50.672 --> 00:41:56.960
essentially no market power and
it has everything to do with

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:58.559
demography.
 

00:41:58.559 --> 00:42:01.469
It also, of course,
has to do with educational

00:42:01.469 --> 00:42:05.534
opportunity,
command of the lingua of the

00:42:05.534 --> 00:42:08.512
country,
all those things,

00:42:08.512 --> 00:42:14.905
but when we talk about the
demographic transition it's this

00:42:14.905 --> 00:42:21.516
ultimately benign story about
going from short lives and many

00:42:21.516 --> 00:42:25.003
babies,
to long lives and fewer babies

00:42:25.003 --> 00:42:26.579
over a period of time.
 

00:42:26.579 --> 00:42:30.992
But there's a huge coercive
aspect to the way it works out

00:42:30.992 --> 00:42:36.179
during the transition for people
who don't have demographic luck.

00:42:36.179 --> 00:42:43.052
Luck of a--luck--big time luck,
historical luck is a pretty big

00:42:43.052 --> 00:42:43.940
thing.
 

00:42:43.940 --> 00:42:51.286
I'll give you another example,
New Haven had very few black

00:42:51.286 --> 00:42:57.818
citizens before World War II,
and at the time that World War

00:42:57.818 --> 00:43:02.695
II, when southern agriculture
was pushing labor off the land

00:43:02.695 --> 00:43:07.820
most of the black families who
ever came to New Haven came here

00:43:07.820 --> 00:43:14.143
in about a fifteen-year period,
and they came in search of

00:43:14.143 --> 00:43:17.030
industrial employment.
 

00:43:17.030 --> 00:43:22.016
Exactly a decade before that
industrial employment collapsed,

00:43:22.016 --> 00:43:23.929
and went guess where?
 

00:43:23.929 --> 00:43:25.659
South.
 

00:43:25.659 --> 00:43:30.590
The industrial employment went
south seeking lower energy costs

00:43:30.590 --> 00:43:33.929
and cheaper labor so that the
economic--

00:43:33.929 --> 00:43:36.409
it's of course a much more
complex story,

00:43:36.409 --> 00:43:38.500
but the timing couldn't have
been worse,

00:43:38.500 --> 00:43:42.315
and Balram's timing in
demographic history couldn't

00:43:42.315 --> 00:43:44.070
have been much worse.
 

